[2]
Date: Wed, 17 Mar 2004 10:32:53 -0000
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Sheparton News, Australia [edited]
<http://news.mcmedia.com.au/story.asp?TakeNo=200403173338428>

Anthrax has struck the Goulburn Valley again, with an outbreak west
of Tatura killing 8 cattle between Thursday and Monday. Department
of Primary Industries senior veterinary officer George Miller said 2
neighbouring properties were involved and had been quarantined. Mr
Miller confirmed the cases were in the same outbreak area of 1997.
One of the properties had been afflicted by the disease previously,
while the other had not.
Mr Miller said a local veterinarian was called on Thursday afternoon
[11 Mar 2004] to investigate a possible anthrax case. He said the
veterinarian had been "pretty sure" it was anthrax, and the DPI was
called to conduct tests, which confirmed the disease's presence on
Friday. "They are only young cattle, so there is no concern for the
milk industry," Mr Miller said.
The 2 farms, which will be quarantined for 42 days, have a combined
total of about 120 20-month-old heifers. He said it was impossible
to know where the cattle had picked up the disease. "It has been
quite dry and dusty, so the cattle could have got it from licking
soil -- cattle normally ingest up to 10 kg of soil per day," Mr
Miller said. [Actually it is more like 2-3 kg. - Mod.MHJ] "The
disease is normally associated with hot and dry weather, but it is
not necessarily the only time -- the last case from the area was in
winter." He said it was also possible that work on a nearby
irrigation channel could have disturbed the [spores], which can live
in soil for up to a decade.
The infected carcasses were burned, and the remaining cattle were
vaccinated. Mr Miller said it was possible there could be further
deaths as the disease and vaccine both have a 10-day incubation
period. Anthrax is caused by the spore-forming bacteria _Bacillus
anthracis_ and is usually contracted through animals eating the
spores. The last major outbreak in the Goulburn Valley, in 1997,
affected 83 properties, took 2 months to clear up, and resulted in
the death of 206 animals. The most recent death was in August 2003,
when a 3-year-old dairy cow died in the Tatura district.
[Byline: Cassie Milner]
--
